pot’, collaboration, ‘naval theatre’, and propaganda in mobilising colonial navalism; the role of naval training within the ‘civilising mission’ and colonial development; and how racial theory influenced naval recruitment, strategy and management, affecting imperial sentiment, ethnic relations, colonial identities, customs and order.This book will appeal to imperial, maritime and regional historians, by broadening our understanding of navies as social and cultural institutions, where power was expressed through the ideas and relations they cultivated, as well as their guns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSea-powerxColoniesxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aSea-powerxColonieszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aSea-powerxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aSea-powerzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xNaval operations, British. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Maritime History & Piracy .2bisacsh  aBritish imperialism.  aCaribbean islands.  aCayman Islanders.  aHong Kong Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve.  aKenya Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve.  aMalacca Straits.  aRoyal Malayan Navy.  aTrinidad Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve.  aZanzibar Naval Volunteer Force.  acolonial naval forces.  apost-war East Africa.  apost-war Hong Kong.1 aSpence, Daniel Owen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610233140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526102331423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526102331/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles